    "answer_id" : 8708594,
    "question_id" : 8708542,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Use <code>retainAll()</code> in the Set interface. This method provides an intersection of elements common in both sets. See the API docs for more information.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 212481,
      "reputation" : 4215,
      "user_id" : 465323,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 94,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/48486463225c6705e51463adcafbb240?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Z&#233;ychin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/465323/z%c3%a9ychin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1325572702,
    "creation_date" : 1325572702,
    "answer_id" : 8708783,
    "question_id" : 8708542,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I would recommend creating a <code>HashMap</code> from set A, and then iterating through set B and checking if any element of B is in A. This would run in <code>O(|A|+|B|)</code> time (as there would be no collisions), whereas <code>retainAll(Collection&lt;?&gt; c)</code> must run in <code>O(|A|*|B|)</code> time.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 433442,
      "reputation" : 1066,
      "user_id" : 818764,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/SzDWW.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Plap",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/818764/plap"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1326583195,
    "creation_date" : 1326583195,
    "answer_id" : 8866211,
    "question_id" : 8708542,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There's a bit rough method to do that. \nIf and only if the A set contains some B's element than the call</p>\n\n<pre><code>A.removeAll(B)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>will modify the A set. In this situation removeAll will return true (As stated at <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/AbstractSet.html#removeAll%28java.util.Collection%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">removeAll docs</a>). But probably you don't want to modify the A set so you may think to act on a copy, like this way:</p>\n\n<pre><code>new HashSet(A).removeAll(B)\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>and the returning value will be true if the sets are not distinct, that is they have non-empty intersection.  </p>\n\n<p>Also see <a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/collections/api-2.1.1/org/apache/commons/collections/CollectionUtils.html#containsAny%28java.util.Collection,%20java.util.Collection%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Apache Commons Collections</a></p>\n"
  }, {
