      "creation_date" : 1671542644,
      "post_id" : 34156551,
      "comment_id" : 132117885,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "I based it on <code>Collections.disjoint</code> source code. If both passed <code>Collection</code>s are <code>java.util.Set</code>s, then there is no check which one is used to iterate over. You might end up with iterating over large set, which gives you the same performance as <code>anyMatch</code> in case <code>setA</code> is large.  <code>Collections.disjoint</code> is in fact more versatile. It performs well with any <code>Collection</code> type, which is not true for <code>anyMatch</code> solution. The OP question was about Java sets, but performance for different collection types is with mentioning."
